04714nam a22007095i 9780824865085DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20072007hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248650857 a10.1515/97808248650852doi  a(DE-B1597)484129  a(OCoLC)256725510  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a306.2/709522221 aAdolphson, Mikael S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Teeth and Claws of the Buddha :bMonastic Warriors and Sohei in Japanese History /cMikael S. Adolphson. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b34 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tTerminology and Translation -- tOne. Discourses on Religious Violence and Armed Clerics -- tTwo. The Contexts of Monastic Violence and Warfare -- tThree. The Fighting Servants of the Buddha -- tFour. The Teeth and Claws of the Buddha: Noble Monks and Monk-Commanders -- tFive. Constructed Traditions :Sōhei and Benkei -- tSix. Sōhei, Benkei, and Monastic Warriors— Historical Perspectives -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tINDEX -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJapan’s monastic warriors have fared poorly in comparison to the samurai, both in terms of historical reputation and representations in popular culture. Often maligned and criticized for their involvement in politics and other secular matters, they have been seen as figures separate from the larger military class. However, as Mikael Adolphson reveals in his comprehensive and authoritative examination of the social origins of the monastic forces, political conditions, and warfare practices of the Heian (794–1185) and Kamakura (1185–1333) eras, these "monk-warriors"(sôhei) were in reality inseparable from the warrior class. Their negative image, Adolphson argues, is a construct that grew out of artistic sources critical of the established temples from the fourteenth century on.In deconstructing the sôhei image and looking for clues as to the characteristics, role, and meaning of the monastic forces, The Teeth and Claws of the Buddha highlights the importance of historical circumstances; it also points to the fallacies of allowing later, especially modern, notions of religion to exert undue influence on interpretations of the past. It further suggests that, rather than constituting a separate category of violence, religious violence needs to be understood in its political, social, military, and ideological contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBuddhismzJapanxHistoryy1185-1600. 0aBuddhismzJapanxHistoryyTo 1185. 0aBuddhist monks as soldierszJapanxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486508540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824865085423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824865085.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE